1️⃣ Why Collections Came Into Java
 Ans:- Before Java Collections Framework, programmers mostly used arrays.
 Example:
 int[] numbers = new int[5];
 Arrays were the primary way to store multiple values.

 But arrays had serious limitations.

 ❌ Problem 1 — Fixed Size
Array size cannot change after creation.
int[] numbers = new int[5];
You can store only 5 values.
If you suddenly need 6 values, the program fails.
To fix it you must:
	1.	Create a new array
	2.	Copy old elements
	3.	Add new element

Example:-
Old Array
[10, 20, 30, 40, 50]
Create New Array
[10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60]
This is slow and inconvenient.

❌ Problem 2 — No Built-in Operations
Arrays only store data.

They do not provide operations like:
	•	add element
	•	remove element
	•	search element
	•	sort elements
	•	check duplicates

Programmers had to write all logic manually.

Example:
Finding element in array:
for(int i=0;i<arr.length;i++)
Every time you must write loops.

❌ Problem 3 — Cannot Easily Handle Complex Data
Suppose you want to store different objects.
Example:
Student
Employee
Order
Product
Arrays are not flexible for managing complex objects.

❌ Problem 4 — No Standard Data Structures
Computer Science already had powerful structures:
	•	Lists
	•	Stacks
	•	Queues
	•	Hash Tables
	•	Trees

But Java originally did not provide a standard library for them.
Every programmer implemented their own version.

Result:
❌ messy code
❌ repeated work
❌ inconsistent implementations